SIMPLE: wife
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wife
<hw>Wife</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Wives</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>wif</ets>, AS.
<ets>wif</ets>; akin to OFries. & OS. <ets>wif</ets>, D.
<ets>wijf</ets>, G. <ets>weib</ets>, OHG. <ets>w⟦imac⟧b</ets>, Icel.
<ets>v⟦imac⟧f</ets>, Dan. <ets>viv</ets>; and perhaps to Skr.
<ets>vip</ets> excited, agitated, inspired, <ets>vip</ets> to tremble,
L. <ets>vibrare</ets> to vibrate, E. <ets>vibrate</ets>. Cf. Tacitus,
[⟦ldquo⟧ Germania⟦rdquo⟧ 8]: Inesse quin etiam sanctum aliquid et
providum putant, nec aut consilia earum aspernantur aut responsa
neglegunt. Cf. <er>Hussy</er> a jade, <er>Woman</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman; an adult female; -- now used in literature
only in certain compounds and phrases, as ale<xex>wife</xex>,
fish<xex>wife</xex>, good<xex>wife</xex>, and the like.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧
Both men and <xex>wives</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the green he saw sitting a <qex>wife</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The lawful consort of a man; a woman who is united
to a man in wedlock; a woman who has a husband; a married woman; --
correlative of <xex>husband</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ The husband of one
<xex>wife</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>1 Tin. iii. 2.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let every one you . . . so love his <qex>wife</qex> even as
himself, and the <qex>wife</qex> see that she reverence her husband.</q>
<rj><qau>Eph. v. 33.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To give to wife</b></col>, <col><b>To take to
wife</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to give or take (a woman) in marriage.</cd>
-- <col><b>Wife's equity</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>the equitable
right or claim of a married woman to a reasonable and adequate
provision, by way of settlement or otherwise, out of her choses in
action, or out of any property of hers which is under the jurisdiction
of the Court of Chancery, for the support of herself and her
children.</cd> <au>Burrill.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wifehood</ent>⟦br⟧
